-- FTSE 100 Index Advances; Inmarsat Rises, Shares of BT Group Fall
-- B y   A d a m   E w i n g
-- 2010-10-11T08:52:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-10/ryanair-holdings-stobart-group-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
U.K. stocks climbed, extending last
week’s 1.2 percent gain.  Smiths Group Plc  and  Inmarsat Plc  rose
while BT Group Plc declined.  Smiths Group, the world’s biggest maker of airport-security
scanners, gained 1.3 percent after its price estimate was
raised, while Inmarsat, the world’s biggest provider of
satellite services, climbed 1.4 percent after Goldman Sachs
Group Inc. recommended the shares. BT Group retreated 1.8
percent after its recommendation was cut at Sanford C. Bernstein
& Co.  The  FTSE 100 Index  rose 0.3 percent to 5,676.29 at 9:44
a.m. in London, paring two days of losses. The gauge has dropped
2.6 percent from this year’s high on April 15 as speculation
grew that European governments’ austerity measures will curb
economic growth while reports from the U.S. pointed to a
slowdown in the world’s largest economy. The FTSE All-Share
Index increased 0.4 percent today, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index
advanced 0.5 percent.  Smiths Group rose 1.3 percent to 1,252 pence, erasing two
days of losses. UBS AG raised its price estimate 11 percent to
1,550 pence.  Inmarsat increased 1.4 percent to 639 pence, up 19 percent
in the past year, after Goldman Sachs raised its recommendation
to “buy” from “neutral,” saying it continues “to see
secular demand for bandwidth supporting longer-term growth in
Inmarsat’s core businesses.”  BT Group  BT Group Plc , the U.K.’s biggest fixed-line phone operator,
fell 1.8 percent to 146.3 pence, dropping for a second day.
Sanford Bernstein cut its rating for BT to “underperform” from
“market perform.”  John Wood Group Plc  jumped 2.7 percent to 441 pence, the
biggest rise this month. The U.K. oil and gas services company
said it expects improved second-half result in its engineering
unit.  Ladbrokes Plc  rose for a seventh day, increasing 2.8
percent to 141.9 pence. The U.K. bookmaker founded in 1886 said
third-quarter operating profit more than doubled, boosted by
betting on soccer’s World Cup and better win rates at its
gambling machines.  To contact the reporter on this story:
